<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="47" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[824,1474,1207,1359]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis box="[862,919,1208,1231]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Notes</emphasis>
. – This rare species is only known from southern 
<collectingCountry box="[824,889,1239,1263]" name="Brazil" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Brazil</collectingCountry>
and from 
<collectingCountry box="[1003,1094,1239,1263]" name="Ecuador" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, where Allioni found it in 
<collectingRegion country="Ecuador" name="Morona-Santiago" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Morona Santiago</collectingRegion>
(Gualaquiza) and 
<collectingRegion box="[1117,1184,1271,1295]" country="Ecuador" name="Azuay" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Azuay</collectingRegion>
. The species is very close to the common 
<taxonomicName box="[970,1104,1304,1327]" class="Jungermanniopsida" family="Lepidoziaceae" genus="Lepidozia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Jungermanniales" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Marchantiophyta" rank="species" species="cupressina">
<emphasis box="[970,1104,1304,1327]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">L. cupressina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and may be a variety of the latter (GRADSTEIN, in press).
</paragraph>
